response:
{"Q0":"Always start on the left-most picture and continue to swap from left-right. There will be 5 total pictures. After the first swap, make sure that if there is a picture to left of your swap, that you check to see if it will swaps behind the picture to double check. Example: 

1) Image 1 swaps with Image 2
2) Image 1 swaps with Image 3
3) You must try to swap Image 2 with Image 3 as you don't know if it's heavier/lighter. In this example, Image 2 is lighter and they don't swap.
4) Image 1 does not swap with Image 4
5) Image 4 swaps with Image 5
6) Image 1 swaps with Image 5
7) Image 3 does not swap with Image 5

There is a full example. In your problem, there should only be one swap, but please remember to use this pattern."}

presented_choices:
["Continue to swap pieces until you have put them as far to the left as they will allow.","Step 1: Designate the leftmost object as Object A.

Step 2: Check if swapping Object A with its right neighbor is valid (based on a predefined rule, such as its weight).

If invalid, designate the right neighbor as the new Object A and repeat Step 2.

If valid, swap their positions, designate the swapped neighbor as Object B, note Object A’s position, and proceed to Step 3.

Step 3: Propagate Object B to the left, following the same logic as Step 2 but with two changes:

The goal direction is now left.

If a swap fails, assume Object B is sorted and return to Step 2 and remember Object A's position."]

["Start by comparing the first two blocks. Then progress by comparing the blocks in the 2nd and 3rd position, and then the 3rd and 4th, and so on.

Whenever a swap happens, keep note of the \"leading\" block that was placed ahead (to the right). If a swap does not happen, the block on the right that was compared becomes the new \"leading\" block. The block that was just swapped behind the \"leading\" block then needs to be compared to the block behind it. If a swap happens, again compare it to the block behind it. Repeat this until a swap does not happen or until it is placed in the first position. Then return to your \"leading\" block and compare it to the block ahead of it.","Step 1: Designate the leftmost object as Object A.

Step 3: Propagate Object B to the left, following the same logic as Step 2 but with two changes:

The goal direction is now left.

If a swap fails, assume Object B is sorted and return to Step 2 and remember Object A's position."]
